General Emergency Response

-Emergency alert system;
-Periodic emergency training for employees;
-Communication systems with local emergency responders and regulatory agencies;
-Emergency drills with Terminal personnel, regulatory agencies, and community emergency responders to enhance response skills and coordination among agencies;
-Mutual Aid with local Fire Departments; and
-Participation with the Local Emergency Planning Committee (LEPC) or its equivalent.

Further, the Lansing LP Terminal complies with the National Fire Protection Association's (NFPA's) Liquefied Petroleum Gas (LPG) Code (NFPA-58) requirements for LP Gas storage. In addition to the presence of appropriate controls to prevent and limit possible releases of butane, if a release does occur, a Smart Plan/Emergency Response Action Plan (ERAP) is in place for the Facility and response activities are coordinated with the Looking Glass Regional Fire Authority and Clinton County Office of Emergency Management (LEPC).

C. FIVE YEAR ACCIDENT HISTORY

The Lansing LP Terminal has an excellent record of accident prevention. The terminal maintains records for all significant accidental chemical releases that occur at this facility inclusive of root-cause analyses and associated follow-up actions, as appropriate.  There have been no accidents within the previous five (5) years resulting in consequences as defined within the EPA RMP reporting requirements.  The Terminal tracks all process incidents per API 754 guidance. 

