These fourteen (14) individual elements of the prevention program work together to prevent accidental chemical releases.  Marathon and its employees are committed to the standards required by these management programs. In addition to the above elements, the Lansing LP Terminal also has specific prevention measures that are employed as part of our operating procedures along with engineering/administrative controls to prevent, identify, and contain/control a release.  These are briefly summarized as follows:

General Risk Reduction and Safety Measures

-Engineering and construction in accordance with Recognized and Generally Accepted Good Engineering Practices and company standards;
-Equipment properly designed with protection from overpressure (pressure safety relief valves, etc.);
-Updated technical drawings, Piping & Instrument Diagrams and Process/Block Flow Diagrams;
-Operating systems monitored and controlled by trained Operators (both on-site and remotely);
-Computerized monitoring and automated process controls;
-Redundant control systems with uninterruptable power supply; 
-Automatic and manual shutdown devices for critical systems;
-Scheduled inspection and testing of instruments, analyzers, and safety devices;
-Controlled facility access;
-Regular safety meetings and safety awareness programs;
-Routinely scheduled safety inspections and audits; and
-Frequent unit surveillance by operators.

